abstract.gco:CharacterString: World Gazetteer represents the locations and proper names for map features around the world. The gazetteer includes attribute and annotation name information from various layers of the Digital Chart of the World. This layer is part of the 2014 ESRI Data and Maps collection for ArcGIS 10.2.

purpose.gco:CharacterString: World Gazetteer provides a base map layer that may be used to find locations by their proper name anywhere around the world. The categories include airports, coastal features, drainage features, land features, ocean features, islands, political features, and populated places.

evaluationMethodDescription.gco:CharacterString: The shapefile is converted to file geodatabase (FGDB) format using tools in ArcGIS. The geometry is checked, and if needed repaired. The data set is created directly from a topologically correct ArcInfo® coverage.

measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: The shapefile is converted to file geodatabase (FGDB) format using tools in ArcGIS. The geometry is checked, and if needed repaired. The data set is created directly from a topologically correct ArcInfo® coverage.
After processing, the data set is checked for drawing display and number of records and file sizes compared with source materials.

The horizontal accuracy, at a 90 percent confidence level for circular error, ranges from 1,600 feet to 7,300 feet. These figures are the root sum square of Operational Navigation Chart (ONC)/Jet Navigation Chart (JNC) sheet positional errors plus the additional error introduced by the Digital Chart of the World production process. Since the features are derived from annotation, they do not correspond with the true location because the latitude and longitude coordinate values were derived from the annotation location rather than the map feature itself. Locations taken from annotation are based on the lower left corner of the first letter. Also, the names associated with fuzzy polygons may occur anywhere in the general area of the feature. For example, the name 'Rocky Mountains' is a point located somewhere in the general area covered by the term Rocky Mountains. Fuzzy polygon names, which appeared on more than one ONC sheet, will occur more than once.

description.gco:CharacterString: The following steps were performed by Esri: Extracted the features from the Digital Chart of the World. Restructured attributes for easier feature classifications. Updated attribute values based on political changes and other factors. Created ArcGIS® layer file (.lyr). Created ArcView GIS legend file (.avl). Created projection file (.prj). Created spatial indices.

The following steps were performed by Esri: Updated FIPS_CNTRY attribute for East Timor and Serbia & Montenegro. Created ArcGIS® layer file (.lyr), projection file (.prj), and spatial indices. Converted the data set to SDC.
The following steps were performed by Esri: Updated attribute values for Taiwan. Removed the Paracel and Spratly island groups.
The following steps were performed by Esri: Reduced the attribute widths for CATEGORY and DESCRIPT.

The following steps were performed by Esri: Duplicated the point for the 'Sea of Japan' and renamed the new point 'East Sea'. Moved the 'Sea of Japan' point closer to Japan and moved the 'East Sea' point closer to the Korean peninsula. Changed name from 'Kiev' to 'Kyiv' for the four records related to Kyiv, Ukraine.

The following steps were performed by Esri: Updated the FIPS_CNTRY attribute for all points in Serbia to 'RB' and in Montenegro to 'MJ'. Converted the data set to SDC. Created projection file (.prj), and spatial indices.

The following steps were performed by Esri: Used Data & Maps 2012 World Countries to select all gazetteer points that fell within South Sudan. Calculated the field WITHIN = 'South Sudan'. Calculated the field FIPS_CNTRY = 'SS'. Converted the data set to SDC. Created ArcGIS® layer file (.lyr), projection file (.prj), and spatial indices.
Converted the dataset into a file geodatabase.
